#compdef hntop hn_top
# Documentation: source-direct extraction from upstream
# BafS/hn-top hn.v (**V language**; uses V's
# stdlib **`flag` module** — `vlang/v vlib/flag/`;
# first documented V (vlang) CLI in the corpus.
# Binary built via `v -o bin/hntop -prod hn.v` per
# README; self-declared application name is `hn_top`
# at hn.v:41 — completion bound to both `hntop`
# (build artifact) and `hn_top` (declared app name)):
#   hn.v line 4 (`import flag` — V package import
#     directive; `flag` is a V STANDARD LIBRARY module
#     shipped with every V toolchain installation,
#     lives at `vlib/flag/flag.v` in the vlang/v
#     source tree)
#   hn.v line 40 (`mut fp := flag.new_flag_parser(
#     os.args)` — V FACTORY: `new_flag_parser`
#     constructs a `FlagParser` value; `mut`
#     declares the binding as MUTABLE so subsequent
#     method calls (which require mut receivers) can
#     modify internal state)
#   hn.v lines 41-44
#     (`fp.application('hn_top')` / `fp.version(
#     'v0.1.0')` / `fp.description('Show top HN
#     news')` / `fp.skip_executable()` — V CASCADE-
#     STYLE CONFIG: each call mutates `fp` in
#     place; no semicolon separator like Tcl/
#     Smalltalk, just successive statements on the
#     same `mut` binding.  `skip_executable()`
#     consumes argv[0] so it isn't parsed as a
#     positional)
#   hn.v line 45 (`top_num := fp.int('num', \`n\`,
#     5, 'number of top news to show')` — V `fp.int
#     (LONG, SHORT, DEFAULT, HELP)` method; `\`n\``
#     is V's BACKTICK-DELIMITED CHARACTER LITERAL
#     (type `u8`, value 110 = ASCII 'n').  `:=`
#     declares + assigns; result is the parsed int
#     value)
#   hn.v line 46 (`source_urls := fp.bool(
#     'source_urls', \`u\`, false, 'show source
#     urls')` — `fp.bool` for boolean flag with
#     short `\`u\``)
#   hn.v lines 48-52 (`fp.finalize() or { eprintln
#     (err); println(fp.usage()); return }` — V
#     `finalize()` returns `![]string` (Result type
#     of string array); `or { ... }` is V's RESULT-
#     TYPE FALLBACK BLOCK; on parse error, write
#     err to stderr, print usage, return.  Note:
#     this example DISCARDS the unparsed-positional
#     return because hntop takes no positionals)
# Reference accessed: 2026-05-31 via gh api.
#
# hntop (compiled name from README's `v -o bin/hntop
# -prod hn.v`) is a **terminal Hacker News top-
# stories reader** in V — fetches top stories from
# the HN Firebase API, prints them with title,
# score, comments, user, and optional source URL.
# Pivots from R299 hetzner-k3s (Crystal Admiral)
# into the **V (vlang) language tooling cluster**
# — corpus's first documented V CLI.  Sister tools:
# vlang/v compiler (already in corpus as `_v`),
# vlang/coreutils (V port of GNU coreutils — many
# would dup with stock OS coreutils).  **MAJOR
# MILESTONE — R300, the THREE-HUNDREDTH harvest
# round of the corpus**: corpus's **first
# documented V CLI** — adds V stdlib `flag` module
# to the cross-language CLI taxonomy (39 library
# variants now).
#
# Critical extraction note: hntop uses **V stdlib
# `flag` module** at hn.v:4 — `import flag`; V's
# stdlib has a CANONICAL flag-parsing module
# (vlib/flag/flag.v).  Distinct from V's separate
# `cli` module (vlib/cli/cli.v) which provides a
# clap-style command tree.  `flag` is the
# LIGHTWEIGHT, IMPERATIVE option — favored for
# small scripts and tools; `cli` is the
# DECLARATIVE, subcommand-friendly option — favored
# for larger apps with subcommands.  vlang/
# coreutils ports use `flag` (mktemp.v, options.v,
# etc.).  Documents the **stdlib-flag-vs-stdlib-
# cli distinction** — V is one of the few
# languages with TWO stdlib CLI modules at
# different abstraction levels.  Sister to Pony's
# single stdlib `cli` (R298 lutra).  Corpus's
# **first documented V CLI**.
#
# Critical extraction note: hntop uses **V backtick
# character literal `\`n\`` for short flags** at
# hn.v:45-46 — V uses BACKTICKS for character
# literals (e.g. `\`n\`` is the byte value 110 =
# ASCII 'n').  Single quotes are V's STRING
# literals; double quotes are also strings (with
# different escape rules).  Documents the **V
# backtick-char-literal CLI flag pattern** — sister
# to R291 CL `#\h`, R292 Erlang `$h`, R295 CL
# clingon `#\A`, R298 Pony `'p'`.  FIVE character-
# literal CLI cluster languages now: CL `#\X`,
# Erlang `$X`, Pony `'X'`, clingon (CL) `#\X`, V
# `\`X\``.  V is UNIQUE in using BACKTICKS — every
# other char-literal language uses some form of
# `#\` (Lisp family) or `$` (Erlang) or single
# quote (Pony).  Corpus's **fifth character-
# literal CLI flag pattern (V's backtick variant)**.
#
# Critical extraction note: hntop uses **V `mut`
# binding for mutable parser handle** at hn.v:40 —
# `mut fp := flag.new_flag_parser(os.args)` —
# `mut` declares the binding as MUTABLE; without
# `mut`, V's IMMUTABILITY-BY-DEFAULT would reject
# the subsequent `fp.application(...)` calls
# because those methods take `mut` receivers.
# Documents the **mutability-must-be-explicit
# parser pattern** — distinct from R290 Racket
# (immutable command spec built via macro), R298
# Pony (handled by `?` partial annotation), and
# R296 Julia (function signature is the spec — no
# binding needed).  V's approach is similar to
# Rust's `let mut` but uses keyword `mut` BEFORE
# the binding instead of `let mut`.  Corpus's
# **first documented mutability-keyword-required
# CLI parser pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: hntop uses **V Result-
# type `or { ... }` fallback for parse errors** at
# hn.v:48-52 — `fp.finalize() or { eprintln(err);
# println(fp.usage()); return }`.  V's `finalize()`
# returns `![]string` (Result-typed string array):
# either the leftover positional args OR an error.
# `or { ... }` is V's UNIQUE Result-fallback block
# — runs ONLY when the Result is an error; inside
# the block, `err` is implicitly bound to the
# IError value.  Documents the **Result-or-block
# pattern** — distinct from R298 Pony `try ... end`
# (exception-style), R293 Tcl `try { ... } trap`
# (error-code list), R296 Julia exception-based,
# and R295 CL clingon Common Lisp condition
# system.  V's `or { }` is a HYBRID: type-checked
# Result + EARLY-RETURN block.  No throw-catch
# unwinding required.  Corpus's **first documented
# V Result-or-block CLI error handling**.
#
# Critical extraction note: hntop uses **V `:=`
# declare-and-bind for parsed values** at hn.v:45/
# 46 — `top_num := fp.int(...)` and `source_urls
# := fp.bool(...)`.  V's `:=` is the SHORT VARIABLE
# DECLARATION operator (sister to Go's `:=`).  The
# parsed value is RETURNED DIRECTLY from the `int`/
# `bool`/`string` method calls — NOT stored on the
# parser as a field to retrieve later.  Documents
# the **method-call-returns-parsed-value pattern**
# — distinct from R295 CL clingon `(cli:getopt
# opts :key)` (parser holds, lookup by key), R294
# Pharo `flags.<name>` accessor (parser holds), and
# R297 Prolog `parse_opt(OptName(Value))` (term
# arrives in handler).  V's approach is the MOST
# DIRECT: declare the variable AT the option-spec
# call site.  Plus V's static typing means each
# call's return type matches the method (`fp.int`
# returns int, `fp.bool` returns bool, `fp.string`
# returns string).  Corpus's **first documented
# direct-return-from-spec-call CLI parser**.
#
# Critical extraction note: hntop uses **V cascade-
# style parser config WITHOUT separator** at hn.v:
# 41-44 — four consecutive method calls on `fp`:
# `fp.application('hn_top')`, `fp.version('v0.1.0
# ')`, `fp.description('Show top HN news')`,
# `fp.skip_executable()`.  Each is a separate V
# statement (no separator; V uses newline-as-
# statement-terminator like Python and Go).
# Distinct from R293 Tcl semicolon-separated
# `;\n`, R294 Pharo cascade `;` (semicolon-
# separated messages to SAME receiver), and R298
# Pony `.>` chained-mutation.  V's "cascade" is
# really just SUCCESSIVE STATEMENTS on a mut
# binding — no special syntax.  Documents the
# **statement-sequence parser configuration
# pattern** — implicit cascading via
# IMMUTABILITY-BY-DEFAULT + mut bindings.
#
# Critical extraction note: hntop uses **`fp.
# application` + `fp.version` for help-text
# metadata** at hn.v:41-43 — V's `flag` module
# accepts application name, version, and
# description as SEPARATE setter calls (not
# constructor args).  Documents the **separate-
# setter-for-help-metadata pattern** — distinct
# from R295 CL clingon `make-command :name "..."`
# (constructor kwarg), R294 Pharo `(ClapCommandSpec
# id: #pillar) description: '...'` (cascade), and
# R296 Julia `@main` (docstring-driven).  V's
# approach is the MOST FRAGMENTED: each metadata
# field is its own method call.  Trade-off: more
# verbose at the call site, but lower-arity
# methods.
#
# Hunt-skip notes: skipped `_v` (V compiler,
# already in corpus + blacklisted), vlang/
# coreutils ports (would dup with stock OS
# coreutils — mktemp, cat, ls, etc. already have
# system completions).  Probed
# `cjyeats73/cos350_projects vtest-parser.v`
# (project-internal tool, no separate binary),
# `phoenixr-codes/im2ansi` (image-to-ansi
# converter, smaller adoption), `greenian/ian-
# vfetch` (system info tool, name `ian-vfetch` is
# author-namespaced), `qtc-de/rpv` (PE decompiler,
# Windows-focused), `medvednikov/v2_old` (V
# language v2 prototype — abandoned), `fdigeron/
# xertools sqlrunner.v` (SQL runner, no obvious
# binary).  Chose hntop: clean focused V `flag`
# spec in one self-contained file with EVERY major
# V flag-module pattern represented (factory,
# cascade config, skip_executable, typed `.int`/
# `.bool`/`.string` methods, backtick char
# literal, `:=` direct binding, finalize() with
# Result-or-block error handling), real GitHub
# project (24 stars, niche but stand-alone), and
# README explicitly documents the binary name as
# `hntop`.

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line

# 2 flags decoded source-direct from hn.v:45-46.
# Note: hntop takes no positional args — the
# `fp.finalize()` return is discarded.
_arguments -s -S \
  '(-n --num)'{-n,--num}'=[number of top news to show (default: 5)]:n:' \
  '(-u --source_urls)'{-u,--source_urls}'[show source URLs]' \
  '--help[show hntop help]' \
  '--version[show hntop version]'
